:: Let's Get Practical [Intro] {"position":"500,500","size":"100,100"}
## Let's Get Practical

<img src="https://i2s.cmmn.com/images/Kits.png" style="max-width:100%" />

### Components
{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>Resistor</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> A resistor limits how much electrical current can flow through a circuit.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> Electricity is like water flowing through a hose. A resistor is like making the hose narrower - less gets through at once. This protects parts that could be damaged by too much electricity.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> Resistors protect LEDs, set signal levels, and control how strongly parts interact.</p>

<div class="tip-box">**Tip:** 
You can use this handy <a href="https://www.digikey.com/en/resources/conversion-calculators/conversion-calculator-resistor-color-code">Resistor Color Code Calculator from DigiKey</a> to identify a resistor.</div>
</div>
</details>
}

{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>Diode</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> A diode allows electricity to flow in one direction, but blocks it from flowing the other way.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> A diode is like a one-way door for electricity - it lets electricity go through one way, but stops it from going backward.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> Diodes prevent reverse current, protect parts, and control the direction of current flow.</p>
</div>
</details>
}

{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>LED</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> An LED (Light Emitting Diode) is a diode that gives off light when current flows through it.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> An LED is a tiny light that turns on when electricity flows through it the correct way.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> LEDs are used as lights, indicators, status signals, and visual outputs.</p>
<div class="warn-box"><strong>Important:</strong> LEDs need a resistor in series. Without one, too much current flows and burns out the LED.</div>
</div>
</details>
}

{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>Capacitor</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> A capacitor stores a small amount of electrical energy and releases it when needed.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> A capacitor is like a tiny rechargeable bucket for electricity - it fills up, holds a charge briefly, and then releases it.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> Capacitors smooth out power, reduce electrical noise, create timing effects, and help stabilize circuits.</p>
</div>
</details>
}

{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>Integrated Circuit (IC)</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> An IC is a tiny chip that contains many electronic parts inside it.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> An IC is like a tiny electronic brain. Instead of building a circuit from lots of separate pieces, many parts are packed into one small chip.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> An IC might control lights, respond to sensors, store logic, amplify signals, or perform a specific function designed by the chip manufacturer.</p>
</div>
</details>
}

{
<details class="component">
<summary><strong>PCB</strong> <span class="expand-icon">▶</span></summary>
<div class="component-body"><p><strong>Simple definition:</strong> A printed circuit board (PCB) is the board that holds electronic parts and connects them together.</p>
<p><strong>Think of it this way:</strong> A PCB is like a map of roads for electricity. The parts sit on the board, and the copper paths show electricity where to go.</p>
<p><strong>In your kit:</strong> The PCB makes assembly easier because the wiring paths are already built into the board.</p>
</div>
</details>
}

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->What Is Soldering]] <!--Let's Get Practical--> [[Next: Basic Technique →->Basic Technique]] </div>



:: Practice and Next Steps [Next-Steps] {"position":"1300,200","size":"100,100"}
## Practice & Next Steps

### Building Skill

* **Start with through-hole kits**: larger pads, slower pace, easy to see what's happening. Look for beginner kits on Adafruit or SparkFun.
* **Practice boards**: dedicated boards with a variety of pad sizes and component types
* **Old/broken electronics**: great low-stakes material for desoldering practice
* **Slow down**: watch the solder flow, develop feel for heat timing, don't rush

### Good Resources

* **Eugene Maker Space** - Join and participate in our Discord and work on projects together!
* **Adafruit Learning System** (adafruit.com/learn) - thorough beginner soldering guides with photos
* **EEVblog on YouTube**: Dave Jones' soldering tutorials are widely considered the best free resource
* **r/soldering on Reddit**: community for joint critique and technique feedback
* **Electrical Basics Made Easy**:  <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYuVSG89vg0">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYuVSG89vg0</a>
** Highly Recommended

### Projects and Kits

* **Micro Racer Kit**: <a href="https://stuckatprototype.com/">https://stuckatprototype.com/ </a> <img src="https://stuckatprototype.com/cdn/shop/files/242A3933.png?v=1750626769&width=350 />


<div class="tip-box">**Fastest way to improve:** Solder something, photograph every joint, post for critique. Specific feedback accelerates skill far faster than solo practice.</div>




:: Preparing Your Workspace [Intro] {"position":"500,800","size":"100,100"}
## Preparing Your Workspace

### Physical Setup

* Work on a **heat-resistant mat**: silicone, ceramic tile, or a proper soldering mat
* Place your iron stand **within easy reach** of your dominant hand
* Ensure **good lighting**: you need to clearly see pads and component leads
* Set up **ventilation**: a fan pulling fumes away, or a dedicated fume extractor

### Before You Start Soldering

* Organize your components and (link:"PCB")[Printed Circuit Board] before turning on the iron
* Know exactly what you're going to solder and plan before you heat
* Heat the iron and **tin the tip** (covered next)
* Have your brass cleaner ready


<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Basic Technique]] <!--Preparing Your Workspace--> [[Next: Safety First →->Safety First]] </div>



:: Reading the Joint [Review] {"position":"900,200","size":"100,100"}
## Reading the Joint

Visually assessing a solder joint is a skill you'll develop quickly with practice.

<img src="https://i2s.cmmn.com/images/common-issues.jpg" style="max-width:100%" />

### Good Joint ✅

* Smooth, shiny surface (slightly matte for lead-free - that's normal)
* Concave/volcano shape - solder wets up the component lead and down onto the pad
* You can see the outline of the pad and lead through the solder

### Cold Joint ❌

* Dull, grainy, or frosted surface
* Rounded blob that didn't wet to the pad properly
* Caused by movement during cooling, iron too cool, or insufficient heat time

### Too Much Solder ❌

* Large blob that obscures the pad and lead entirely
* Risks bridging adjacent pads → short circuit

### Solder Bridge ❌

* Solder spanning between two adjacent pads or leads
* Creates a short circuit - always inspect after soldering fine-pitch ICs

<div class="tip-box">**Use a magnifier or your phone camera** to inspect joints, especially on small components.</div>




:: Safety First [Intro] {"position":"500,950","size":"100,100"}
## Safety First ⚠️

<div class="warn-box">**The iron tip runs at 300-400°C. (text-colour:red)+(bg:yellow)[Burns happen instantly and without warning.]**</div>

### Key Safety Rules

* **Eye protection**: always wear safety glasses
* **Ventilation**: solder fumes (flux vapor) are irritating; work near a fan or fume extractor
* **Never touch the tip**: use a stand at all times when the iron is hot
* **Lead handling**: if using leaded solder, wear gloves and wash your hands afterwards
* **Fire hazard**: keep flammables away and never leave a hot iron unattended
* **Cable management**: keep the iron cord away from the tip and your work area

<div class="tip-box">**Tip:** Return the iron to its stand between every operation. Most burns happen when an iron is set down "just for a second."</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Preparing Your Workspace]] <!--Safety First--> [[Next: Tinning the Tip →->Tinning the Tip]] </div>



:: Soldering Iron Tips [Next-Steps] {"position":"1300,450","size":"100,100"}
## Soldering Iron Tips

### What's in a Tip?

<img src="https://i2s.cmmn.com/images/soldering-iron-tip.png" style="max-width:100%" />

### Choosing a Tip

<img src="https://i2s.cmmn.com/images/soldering-iron-tip-types.png" style="max-width:100%" />

<div class="tip-box">**Tip choice:** Chisel or bevel tips transfer heat more efficiently than fine conical tips for most through-hole and pad work. Use fine tips for precision (link:"SMD")[Surface Mount Device] work only.</div>



